"Major League Baseball had 40 players and staff members test positive for COVID-19 in the past week, creating a sense of urgency in labor negotiations between the owners and players, according to two persons with direct knowledge of the situation ... The players postponed their vote Sunday whether to accept or reject MLB’s plan for a 60-game season with full pro-rated play after commissioner Rob Manfred telephoned union chief Tony Clark and e-mailed tweaks to MLB’s last proposal ... MLB still is offering 60 games, guaranteeing the players about $1.5 billion, but the recent surge of positive tests now will further delay the start season. The resumption of spring training now will be no earlier than June 29, with the season starting July 26." https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2020/06/21/mlb-2020-deal-season-schedule/3233083001/

I'm reducing the probability that the first game will be before July 16. Monday's MLB conference call just ended saying they will have to negotiate the health and safety terms with the MLBPA while they set the schedule. So maybe it can still happen but Manfred just when on the record saying he is no longer confident there will be a season at all. Could all be negotiating tactics. Need a week for to move players to spring training then 3 weeks of training so if the agreement on non-salary terms is not there in a few days, the season would start after the 16th.

I asked for clarification (if only for my own peace of mind) as to make certain we are talking about the first official, regular season game. I know the question implies that, but the verbiage is too vague for my tastes. After all, spring training has already occurred and one could argue the first MLB game of 2020 has already been played. We should be clear that we are forecasting regular season.

"...Once the season is scheduled -- either because Manfred does so unilaterally or the two sides come to an agreement -- teams will need about 10 days to prepare their training camp sites. An abbreviated three-week spring training would follow. MLB wants the regular season to end no later than Sept. 27 to ensure the postseason doesn't extend into November. Based on that, spring training would have to begin no later than early-to-mid July for a 50-ish game season." https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/mlbpa-rejects-latest-proposal-tells-mlb-to-schedule-2020-season-tell-us-when-and-where/
I'm clawing back my aggressive and uncharacteristic "all in" -- I'm cynical about owners and players coming to an agreement and am equally cynical about both sides' enthusiastic desire to get paid.

I think that the chances of games in first half of July have increased a bit recently because MLB is proceeding with plans for that. The major issue seems to be whether player compensation can be agreed. Most likely outcome is still a delay till after July 16 or a complete cancellation.

The only hitch in an early July start seems to be the revenue sharing plan. I think that there's a better than even chance that the two sides come to some agreement in time to play. Both sides are motivated to get the deal done, and they have a decent amount of time to agree on something and still start before July 16. New report yesterday suggested that MLB could start as early as mid-May, but I think that is overly aggressive. I think how Korean baseball league fairs with their return will have a significant impact on how MLB approaches theirs. Not to mention, will need several weeks to ramp guys back up and they likely will not even be able to get together until mid-May. I see beginning to mid June being the earliest, with beginning of July being most likely.

There is a push to start baseball in Arizona as early as May (https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mlb/news/mlb-opening-day-2020-baseball-when-date-countdown/5zmj59xogfhf1lqvud4v8h38r), which seems very optimistic considering at a March 25 press conference, state Health Director Dr. Cara Christ said that if infections continue at their current pace, illnesses would peak in April and hospitalizations would peak in May (https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-health/2020/04/06/coronavirus-covid-19-arizona-update-monday-april-6-cases-2-456-65-known-deaths/2952287001/). Also, the players need time to practice and get in "game" shape.
MLB already talking about playing games in empty stadiums as early as may.

I'm updating my forecast because the MLB just announced a plan to play games during the coronavirus pandemic. The plan seems a little bit out there though, and has not been agreed upon. The plan looks like it would take effect as early as May, but they said June is more realistic. This looks like a desperation move, and desperation moves often fail. I'm more optimistic, but not that optimistic.

The closest comparison class I can find is the outbreak of Pneumonic plague in Britain in 1349. The outbreak in the 14th Century England lasted roughly nine months... from November, 1348 until June, 1349. Pneumonic plague was a follow-on of Bubonic plague; aka ‘The Black Death’ which reached Britain in late 1348.

The virus is allegedly not thermophilic. Therefore, an outdoor event would benefit from the heat to kill the virus. In history, many pandemics have waves. Ceteris paribus, one might anticipate that as the weather changes in the fall, there is a higher likelihood of disease resurgence.
Some additional "Pre-Season" games may be required. Coronavirus needs to ramp down significantly. American public wants baseball season to begin for restoration of normalcy.

comparing Italy response to American, 1 month behind, similar curves. If American cases start leveling off in 5 weeks, there will still be at least a 3-4 week buffer from when things could restart to when MLB is prepared to offer regular season product

In reviewing other comments, it seems a significnat number of people think the coronavirus "thing" will be over at some point soon and at that point baseball games will start back up. That's not my thinking. On this timeframe I think it is still going to be raging. Perhaps a sense of normalcy will be returning towards the end of this period but I think that's unlikely.

Sad as it is to me, there’s little chance that games will be played until the summer. There may be games with limited number of fans , but if played at all, will be when virus across the country and Canada is largely eradicated or easily treatable. I don’t see that until mid- to late- summer if at all.
It would not be financially sustainable to host baseball games in empty stadiums, and social distancing will continue for all of 2020

SARS lasted about 6 months. And these games can be played without spectators and just watched on TV. So, I don't see much impediment to them playing, even if the outbreak is still going on. It will give us something to watch.

Major update to my numbers (toward a later date). Based on what I've read, there's almost no way a vaccination will be ready by this summer, so the resumption of games in my estimation will happen when the fear of infection abates significantly. I also believe there's a very good chance that when games do resume, they will be to empty stadiums. If one accepts that possibility, a summer resumption is more plausible.
Many experts predict that we are currently in a crucial point in America for this virus. Unless a vaccine is developed, we are unlikely to see any organized sport until early/mid summer.

The US has At least 3 months of this to go. There’s no way there will be focus on sport and venues will struggle to get up and running again for a while after being closed. Plus the risk of a wider breakdown in the US is higher than many places because there are too many guns which risk making escalation excessive. Sport will not be top of the agenda when people have to money to eat.

The disease will cycle maximize through the US in a minimum of 45 days, with a downside from the peak lasting just as long. This disease itself will roll though the entire US peaking at different times in different locations. Since the shortest possible timeline is 3-4 months in the early locations, the entire event will extend in later locations out further in time. Since, baseball teams travel throughout the country they cannot play before the event washes completely out of all locations. And this assumes that the mitigation strategies will be unsuccessful .
Suggesting July 1st

I think it very unlikely that the situation in the USA will improve enough for large events (or for team travel) by mid July. However, in the event that things begin to improve, due to warm weather, etc, there would be large pressure to begin the season on July 4 or after the scheduled all-star break on July 9.
Considering the uncertainty of COVID19 it doesn't look possible before July 1st 2020
The season will likely be cancelled.
CDC guidance of two months to avoid large gatherings, plus other uncertainties make it seem like midsummer is the earliest the season could start.

Similar to the NBA, the exponential growth curve for the US still will cause pervasive changes through mid-May. With the recovery for China taking nearly 2 months from initial infection and continued lockdown elements, the risks associated with hosting a game will be too much risk for baseball owners and players. Normalcy will take longer than July 16th to begin, with a small likelihood of starting late June to help with America's passtime.

Readjusting. China took January, February and March to bring under control. US did not really respond until March though US had cases before that. March, April, May under best of circumstances to work through the crisis. June ir July earliest. Probably need constant updating.

The estimates on when things will get better just keeps on slipping, and really, there is no way to start things up again unless there is a vaccine or it is found that this shelter order is effective is curtaining the coronavirus, and then find a way to start society up again, without having mass infections. Just really negative that anything can be done before July 16th.

We'll see. Most likely all parties are deliberating. Some teams may opt into a soft roll out. Captive audience, people are home and likely interested in some form of diversion. Players likely aren't thrilled and the risk is still apparent. Advertisers and proponents of progressive pace of game changes will suggest this is an opportunity.

They won't have a vaccine for a while, and right now the only way for the US to stop coronavirus is to try to eliminate the spread of it, and then start isolating where the outbreaks are coming from. Right now there are not enough testing kits to test people, so we don't really know how many people have the virus. The bay area is in a shelter in place and my friend who is a doctor at UC Davis said that they were preparing in case there is a big surge in coronavirus patients in 4-9 days.

MLB announced they were pushing back season in accordance with CDC recommendation of restricting events to 50 or fewer people. Thats second week in May.
